<subsection xml:id="subsec-area-of-irregular-polygons" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Area of Irregular Polygons</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction xml:id="auto_6mk7fmjt">
            <p xml:id="auto_xop8ep1j">
            <dl>
                <li xml:id="auto_4dnr2iv9">
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_103wgni9">
                        2.0 Measurements and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_i7tooji7">
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_2iuba2eq">
                        2.5 Area of Polygons
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_erut1i4t">
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_ggxaefgf">
                        Determine the area of irregular polygons in different situations. Explore the area of polygons as used in real-life situations.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_z4ek1n78" component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_k436jt6z">
                        10
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_trsy8ixs" component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_0wut1ukw">
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_lugk4ywa" component="lesson-plan">
                <p xml:id="auto_k8qjdddx"> Upon completion of this lesson, learners will be able to:
                <ol>
                    <li xml:id="auto_icf3dxdp">
                        <p xml:id="auto_m8ggsa3h">
                            <alert>Know (Conceptual Understanding):</alert> Understand that irregular polygons can be divided into smaller familiar shapes (triangles, rectangles, trapeziums) to calculate area, and that the sum of interior angles follows the formula <m>(n-2) \times 180^\circ</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_30ygr7y1">
                        <p xml:id="auto_4dd2emxw">
                            <alert>Do (Procedural Skill):</alert> Divide irregular polygons into triangles, rectangles, and trapeziums, measure the necessary dimensions, and calculate the total area by summing individual areas.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_aw0b9q9m">
                        <p xml:id="auto_p2plwh2s">
                            <alert>Apply (Application/Problem-Solving):</alert> Solve real-life problems involving the area of irregular polygons such as land surveying, garden design, and flooring cost calculations.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
                </p>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>
        <axiom component="resources">
        <!-- Link to blurb -->
        <xi:include href="../../resources-blurb-lesson.ptx" />

        <sbsgroup widths="45% 45%" margins="2% 2%">
            <sidebyside>
                <p xml:id="auto_ta1bignz">
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/area-of-polygons/area-of-irregular-polygons.pdf"> Lesson Plan </dataurl>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_c5coekmt">
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/area-of-polygons/step-by-step-guide_area-of-irregular-polygons.pdf"> Step-by-Step Guide </dataurl>
                </p>
            </sidebyside>
        </sbsgroup>
    </axiom>
    <xi:include href="../../resources-materials.ptx" />

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 1: Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_eenaeza4">
            <alert>Duration:</alert> 15 minutes
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_a6czxcdp">
            <alert>Anchor Activity: Dividing Irregular Polygons into Smaller Shapes</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_ejwuq8pz">
            Students will now work through the activity below, discovering that irregular polygons can be divided into smaller, familiar shapes (triangles, rectangles, trapeziums) to calculate their total area.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_rlaht1zs">
            <alert>Discussion Questions:</alert>
            <ol marker="(a)">
                <li xml:id="auto_dpn1jpfp"><p xml:id="auto_os6089e7">What makes a polygon irregular?</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_ivcn4byi"><p xml:id="auto_6cez35gz">How did you decide where to divide your polygon?</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_jzvihvls"><p xml:id="auto_lhimwzj4">Did everyone divide their polygon the same way? Why or why not?</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_kptk2a7y"><p xml:id="auto_jusdj13j">What formulas did you use to find the area of each smaller shape?</p></li>
            </ol>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_qx23b5ne">
            <alert>Teacher Role During Discovery:</alert>
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_hxmy7qt2"><p xml:id="auto_g5i8zcor">Circulate among groups, ensuring students understand how to divide the polygon strategically.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_z6mkci94"><p xml:id="auto_7eso0z4y">Ask probing questions: <em>Why did you choose to divide it this way? What shapes did you create?</em></p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_bg0nusz1"><p xml:id="auto_z5li3aq9">For struggling groups: <em>Let us try dividing this polygon into two triangles first. Can you see where to draw the line?</em></p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_ee35p8rc"><p xml:id="auto_ohnor2jq">For early finishers: <em>Can you find a different way to divide the same polygon? Do you get the same total area?</em></p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_1u6ay0o9"><p xml:id="auto_yf2plrhy">Guide students to articulate: Irregular polygons can be broken into smaller shapes, and we add their areas to find the total.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_vh8fhpag"><p xml:id="auto_vwckrw49">Identify 2–3 groups with different division strategies to share with the class.</p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <activity xml:id="auto_nqyrj5br">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_l98odfyp">
               Graph Paper (preferably colored)
            </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_1t1rkqu0">
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_47jr0z8f">
            Scissors
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_azx8b9pc">
            Glue or tape
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_xf1jm7at">
            Rulers
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_msidsfkm">
            Graph paper (optional)
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_h6f8ilw0">
            Measuring tape (optional)
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_v2i0mna9">
            A variety of irregular polygons (either printed or hand-drawn)
            </p>
            <sidebyside>
                <p xml:id="auto_1onz9c6j">
                <ul xml:id="auto_0i5g5ua7">
                    <li xml:id="auto_dqtsgkjj">
                        <p xml:id="auto_qm6ug6vk">
                            work with a printed or drawn irregular polygon. The task is to divide the irregular polygon into smaller shapes whose areas are easier to calculate (like triangles, rectangles, or trapeziums).

                            Tip: Use straight lines to cut along the diagonals or through the middle of the shape to create triangles or rectangles.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_4yo1opf8">
                        <p xml:id="auto_o709qldn">
                                For each smaller shape, ask students to measure the necessary dimensions:
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_hp3ez6rz">
                            For triangles, they need the base and height.
                        </p>
                            <p xml:id="auto_ej8ofufm">

                            For rectangles, they need the length and width.
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_hsk2nas8">
                          For trapeziums, they need the lengths of the two parallel sides and the height.
                       </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_9n79kxuy">
                        <p xml:id="auto_3iitudk8">
                            Calculate the Area of Each Shape: Once the polygon is broken into smaller shapes, students can calculate the area of each shape using appropriate formulas
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_9rkjrywb">
                        <p xml:id="auto_22byn9r9">
                            Add the Areas:
                                Once the area of each smaller shape has been calculated, students should add up all the areas to find the total area of the original irregular polygo
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </p>
              <image>
        <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}
                % Define the coordinates of the irregular heptagon
                    \coordinate (1) at (0,0);
                    \coordinate (2) at (3,0);
                    \coordinate (3) at (4,2);
                    \coordinate (4) at (2,4);
                    \coordinate (5) at (5,6);
                    \coordinate (6) at (0,7);
                    \coordinate (7) at (-2,3);

                    % Draw the heptagon
                    \filldraw[thick,cyan!50] 
                        (1) -- (2) -- (3) -- (4) -- (5) -- (6) -- (7) -- cycle;
                    
                    % Draw interior angle arcs in blue
                    \foreach \p in {1,2,3,4,5,6,7}
                    \draw[thick,blue] (\p) circle(0.3);

                    % Draw exterior angle arcs in red
                    \foreach \p in {1,2,3,4,5,6,7}
                    \draw[thick, dashed,red] (\p) circle(0.5);
                    
                    % Add concave angle markers
                    \draw[-&gt;, thick] (6, 3.5) -- (2,4);
                    \draw[-&gt;, thick] (7, 4) -- (5,6);
                    
                    % Labels and annotations
                    \node[left] at (1) {1};
                    \node[below] at (2) {2};
                    \node[right] at (3) {3};
                    \node[above] at (4) {4};
                    \node[right] at (5) {5};
                    \node[left] at (6) {6};
                    \node[left] at (7) {7};

                    % Description text
                    \node[right, text width=6cm] at (6,3) 
                        {This polygon has several different-sized angles. 
                        With angles more than 180$^\circ$, this shape is a concave polygon.};

            \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
        </image>
            </sidebyside>
        </statement>
    </activity>
        <p xml:id="auto_anpivwgy">
            Regardless of shape, all polygons are made up of the same parts, sides, vertices, interior angles and exterior angles which may varry in size thus describing why we have irregular polygons versus regular polygons. 
        </p>
        
   
          <p xml:id="auto_mkhzsepw">
            An irregular polgon has a set of atleast two sides or angles that are not the same. This heptagon has many different size angles , making it irregular.
        </p>
       

    <p xml:id="auto_k7033nl4">
        The interior angles of an irregular nenagon (9 sides) add up to <m>1,260^\circ</m>. 
        Because angles are different sizes, individual angles cannot be found the sum of the interior angle. 
    </p>
    <image>
    <latex-image label="irregular-nenagon">
        \begin{tikzpicture}
            % Define the coordinates of an irregular nonagon (doubled in size)
            \coordinate (1) at (0,0);
            \coordinate (2) at (4,1);
            \coordinate (3) at (7,3);
            \coordinate (4) at (8,6);
            \coordinate (5) at (6,9);
            \coordinate (6) at (3,10);
            \coordinate (7) at (-1,8);
            \coordinate (8) at (-2,5);
            \coordinate (9) at (-1,2);
            
            % Draw the nonagon
            \filldraw[thick,cyan!60] (1) -- (2) -- (3) -- (4) -- (5) -- (6) -- (7) -- (8) -- (9) -- cycle;
            
            % Add text annotations
            \node[above] at (9) {9 sides};
            \draw[-&gt;] (0.5,10) -- (0.5,8.5);
            \draw[-&gt;] (-3,2) -- (-1,2);
            \draw[-&gt;] (2,4) -- (3,5.7);
            
            % \draw[-&gt;] (-1,5.5) -- (0.5,7.5);
            % \draw[-&gt;] (2,4) -- (3,5.7);
            \node[above] at (0.5,10) {number of sides};
            
            % Label the vertices in the new order
            \node[left] at (1) {1};
            \node[below] at (2) {2};
            \node[right] at (3) {3};
            \node[right] at (4) {4};
            \node[above right] at (5) {5};
            \node[above] at (6) {6};
            \node[left] at (7) {7};
            \node[left] at (8) {8};
            % \node[below left] at (9) {9};
            
            % Equation for sum of interior angles
            \node[right] at (0,8) {\Huge$(9 - 2) \times 180^\circ$};
            \node[right] at (1,6) {\Huge$= 1,260^\circ$};
            \node[right] at (2,4) {sum of its interior angles};
            
            % Add description
            \node[below, text width=15cm] at (0,0) {\textbf{Irregular nonagon}\\
            The interior angles of an irregular nonagon (9 sides) add up to 1,260$^\circ$. 
            Because the angles are different sizes, individual angles cannot be found from the sum of the interior angles.};
        \end{tikzpicture}
    </latex-image>
    </image>

        <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 2: Structured Instruction</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_ljr8nlx0">
            <alert>Duration:</alert> 10 minutes
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_wulwk2g6">
            <alert>Scaffolding Strategies to Address Misconceptions:</alert>
        </p>
        <tabular top="medium" bottom="medium" left="medium" right="medium">
            <row>
                <cell><alert>Misconception</alert></cell>
                <cell><alert>Clarification</alert></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>I can use a formula directly for irregular polygons</cell>
                <cell>There is no single formula for irregular polygons. You must divide it into smaller shapes first</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>There is only one correct way to divide the polygon</cell>
                <cell>No, there are multiple ways. As long as you divide it completely and accurately, you will get the same total area</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>I need to find all the interior angles first</cell>
                <cell>No, you only need the dimensions (base, height, length, width) of the smaller shapes you create</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>Irregular polygons do not have any patterns</cell>
                <cell>While sides and angles vary, the sum of interior angles still follows the formula <m>(n-2) \times 180^\circ</m></cell>
            </row>
        </tabular>
        <p xml:id="auto_h1wyz53r">
            <alert>Formalizing the Method and Addressing Misconceptions</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_nqni9wym">
            After students have completed the anchor activity and shared their findings, walk through the key takeaways in the insight box above. Emphasize:
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_va71a8a1">
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_3x33znb0"><p xml:id="auto_2gfvf5oe">The distinction between regular and irregular polygons (at least two sides or angles that are not the same).</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_ypj9qspj"><p xml:id="auto_pxejc38n">The four-step method: divide, measure, calculate, add.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_zfcnpr5z"><p xml:id="auto_lyo56eez">Use the misconceptions table to proactively address common errors students may have shown during the activity.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_rvezkgy4"><p xml:id="auto_sd0m24g2">Ask students to compare their division strategies: <em>Did different groups get the same total area using different divisions? Why?</em></p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <insight xml:id="auto_t8r0z6iy">
        <p xml:id="auto_hxz92h2y">
           Regardless of shape, all polygons are made up of the same parts: sides, vertices, interior
            angles and exterior angles which may vary in size thus describing why we have irregular
            polygons versus regular polygons. 
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_gdcbq2zk">
            An irregular polygon has a set of at least two sides or angles that are not the same. This heptagon has many different size angles, making it irregular.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_8xa6jgnh">
            The interior angles of an irregular nonagon (9 sides) add up to 1,260 degrees. Because angles are different sizes, individual angles cannot be found from the sum of the interior angles.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_lj1uec0n">
            <alert>Method for Finding Area of Irregular Polygons:</alert>
            <ol markers="1.">
                <li xml:id="auto_h4wk9wd9">
                    <p xml:id="auto_q6r7w2n7">
                        Divide the irregular polygon into smaller, familiar shapes (triangles, rectangles, trapeziums).
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_3e9unn8a">
                    <p xml:id="auto_jhditu8u">
                        Measure the necessary dimensions for each smaller shape.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_337dk7rm">
                    <p xml:id="auto_fv9rtde7">
                        Calculate the area of each smaller shape using the appropriate formula.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_m4dei3h1">
                    <p xml:id="auto_w4hnrgvu">
                        Add all the areas together to find the total area of the irregular polygon.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </insight>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 3: Practice and Application</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_68caj4o6">
            <alert>Duration:</alert> 10 minutes
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_w80c6368">
            <alert>Worked Example (Teacher-Led):</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_4uq57hts">
            Walk through examples on the board before students attempt the exercises independently.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_503dac6f">
            <alert>Teaching Tips:</alert>
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_sw8lll9g"><p xml:id="auto_v844f1m0">Emphasize that heights must be measured perpendicular to the base.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_bxkkkopv"><p xml:id="auto_uazmnlfy">Remind students that since exact heights are not always given, they should show their method and reasoning.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_2llgvk2s"><p xml:id="auto_alvefoqw">Encourage students to sketch the division on paper before calculating.</p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 4: Assessment</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_smy8njrb">
            <alert>Duration:</alert> 5 minutes
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_570cmo3o">
            Students complete the exercises below individually as an exit ticket.
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <exercises xml:id="exercises-area-of-irregular-polygons">
        <title>Exercises</title>

        <exercise xml:id="ex-irregular-hexagon-perimeter">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_jhgs4ov1">
                    A garden is shaped like an irregular hexagon with side lengths <m>4 \, \text{m}, \; 6 \, \text{m}, \; 5 \, \text{m}, \; 7 \, \text{m}, \; 8 \, \text{m}</m> and <m>3 \, \text{m}</m>. Calculate its perimeter.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p xml:id="auto_h81ewn6g">
                    The perimeter is the sum of all side lengths:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>P \amp = 4 + 6 + 5 + 7 + 8 + 3</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp = 33 \, \text{m}</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="ex-heptagonal-garden-fencing">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_1dsqhar1">
                    A heptagonal garden has side lengths of <m>5 \, \text{m}, \; 7 \, \text{m}, \; 6 \, \text{m}, \; 8 \, \text{m}, \; 9 \, \text{m}, \; 6 \, \text{m}</m> and <m>10 \, \text{m}</m>. The owner wants to fence the garden. Calculate the total length of fencing required.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p xml:id="auto_o3iywfrk">
                    The total length of fencing is the perimeter:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>P \amp = 5 + 7 + 6 + 8 + 9 + 6 + 10</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp = 51 \, \text{m}</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="ex-heptagonal-plot-perimeter">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_4pey5tn8">
                    A heptagonal plot of land has side lengths of <m>8 \, \text{m}, \; 10 \, \text{m}, \; 12 \, \text{m}, \; 9 \, \text{m}, \; 11 \, \text{m}, \; 13 \, \text{m}</m> and <m>7 \, \text{m}</m>. Find its perimeter.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p xml:id="auto_83x9b6cs">
                    <md>
                        <mrow>P \amp = 8 + 10 + 12 + 9 + 11 + 13 + 7</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp = 70 \, \text{m}</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>
    </exercises>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Differentiation Strategies</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_onts124s">
            <alert>For Struggling Learners:</alert>
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_tms7kv3c"><p xml:id="auto_w7ct4gue">Provide pre-divided polygons with shapes already outlined.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_spcizu0v"><p xml:id="auto_b87r699v">Use simpler polygons that divide into only 2–3 shapes.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_9hs53wyl"><p xml:id="auto_phyza8o1">Pair struggling students with confident problem solvers.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_pnqlaifn"><p xml:id="auto_kznjbyiw">Provide step-by-step calculation templates.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_uhof9xyq"><p xml:id="auto_r7cf1w8l">Allow use of calculators.</p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_7q9dr10v">
            <alert>For On-Level Learners:</alert>
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_thwim4in"><p xml:id="auto_ra43vpoa">Encourage students to find multiple ways to divide the same polygon.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_h3c3qb0x"><p xml:id="auto_kngiuiwi">Ask students to explain which division strategy is most efficient and why.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_5eul6ax0"><p xml:id="auto_z31johwc">Provide mixed practice with different types of irregular polygons.</p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_nul59htf">
            <alert>For Advanced Learners:</alert>
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_xgoxrs0i"><p xml:id="auto_9tx9f35t">Challenge students to create their own irregular polygons and calculate the area.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_99epizmp"><p xml:id="auto_e50owjya">Explore real-world applications: land surveying, architecture, urban planning.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_edecnu12"><p xml:id="auto_nqk86k1m">Investigate the relationship between different division strategies and efficiency.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_40mn8ppb"><p xml:id="auto_58wfjppd">Apply coordinate geometry to find areas of irregular polygons on a coordinate plane.</p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_rjxzot94">
            <alert>Extension Activity: Real-World Land Surveying Project</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_xwwe4oxi">
            Students work in groups to design an irregular plot of land and calculate its area for a real-world scenario (farm, park, building site).
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_jhc4j7og">
            Tasks:
            <ol marker="(a)">
                <li xml:id="auto_xwiw0nlo"><p xml:id="auto_dhpe75ye">Choose a real-world application that uses irregular polygon shapes (farm land, city park, building site, garden).</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_7fatpvs8"><p xml:id="auto_q81t0h7v">Draw the irregular polygon on graph paper with appropriate dimensions.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_pf1kz5cx"><p xml:id="auto_tf1wnhaw">Divide the polygon into smaller shapes (triangles, rectangles, trapeziums).</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_uys57u4o"><p xml:id="auto_4i7watf2">Measure or specify the necessary dimensions for each smaller shape.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_8b5hcpdc"><p xml:id="auto_1in4z53u">Calculate the area of each smaller shape.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_hdkluln0"><p xml:id="auto_8dwr8txf">Add all the areas together to find the total area.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_o4kjpx43"><p xml:id="auto_an3zbjq8">Present findings to the class, explaining the division strategy and calculations.</p></li>
            </ol>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_e3cm0pca">
            <alert>Key Takeaway:</alert> Students should understand how the method for finding the area of irregular polygons is used in real-world professions such as surveying, architecture, and urban planning to calculate areas of land, buildings, and public spaces.
        </p>
    </axiom>

